Toy examples: Partitions of 2D velocity fields

This is an R Markdown document to illustrate the basic operations of random partitions on velocity fields. The goal is it to evaluate Bayes factors for different example fields.

First example: One rotation

In this exmaple we simulate a case where spliting the partitions has a lower probabilty, thus the Bayes factor is above 1.

Create transformation matrices

# Dimension of velocity field
dimension = 2

# Rotation matrix
R = diag(dimension + 1)
angle = pi/10
R[1, 1] = cos(angle)
R[1, 2] = -sin(angle)
R[2, 1] = sin(angle)
R[2, 2] = cos(angle)

Create and visualize velocity fields

# Load library
library(expm, quietly = TRUE)
source("HelperFunctions.R")

# Create the grid
size = 5
createEmptyGrid(size)

noOfVoxels = length(-size:size)^2
V = matrix(0, dimension, noOfVoxels)
X = matrix(0, dimension + 1, noOfVoxels)

# Generate fields
currentIndex = 1
for (i in -size:size) {
    for (j in -size:size) {
        X[, currentIndex] = c(i, j, 1)
        currentIndex = currentIndex + 1
    }
}
V = logm(R)[1:2, ] %*% X

# Visualize fields
visualizeVelField(V, X, "black")

Split velocity field in half

# First partition
V1 = V[, 1:61]
X1 = X[, 1:61]
plot.new()
createEmptyGrid(size)
visualizeVelField(V = V1, X = X1, color = "red")


# Second partition
V2 = V[, 62:121]
X2 = X[, 62:121]
plot.new()
createEmptyGrid(size)
visualizeVelField(V = V2, X = X2, color = "blue")

Bayes factor with fixed \( \sigma_v^2 \)

Marginal likelihood

Equation from our GSI 2013 paper:

\[ p(\boldsymbol{v} | \mu,\Gamma,\sigma_{v}^{2}) = \int p(\boldsymbol{v}|\Phi \boldsymbol{m},\sigma_{v}^{2}) p(\boldsymbol{m}|\mu,\Gamma) d\boldsymbol{m} = \frac{|\sigma_v^2 \Gamma|^{1/2}}{(2\pi \sigma_v^2)^{dN/2} |\sigma_v^2 \check{\Gamma}|^{1/2}} \exp \left( \frac{1}{2 \sigma_{v}^{2} } \boldsymbol{v}^t\Phi (\sigma_v^2 \check{\Gamma})^{-1} \Phi^t \boldsymbol{v} \right) \] where \( \check{\Gamma} \) is the posterior concentration matrix: \[ \check{\Gamma} = \frac{1}{\sigma_v^2} \Phi^t \Phi + \Gamma \]

Hyperparameters

To compare with fixed multivariate normal noise \( \Sigma \) (next section), we introduce a columnwise parameterize of the concentration matrix:

\[ K \otimes I_d = \sigma_v^2 \Gamma \]

variance = 1e-05
B = diag(c(100, 100, 1))
Gamma = B %x% diag(1, dimension)

Ratio of marginal likelihoods

computeMarginalLikelihoodFixedLowercaseSigma <- function(V, X, Gamma, variance) {
    d = dim(V)[1]
    N = dim(V)[2]
    X[1:d, ] = t(scale(t(X[1:d, ]), center = TRUE, scale = FALSE))

    Phi = matrix(0, 0, d * (d + 1))
    for (i in 1:N) {
        Phi = rbind(Phi, t(X[, i]) %x% diag(1, 2))
    }

    GammaCheck = 1/variance * t(Phi) %*% Phi + Gamma
    normalizingConstant = 1/2 * log(det(variance * Gamma)) - d * N/2 * log(2 * 
        pi * variance) - 1/2 * log(det(variance * GammaCheck))
    marginalLikeihood = normalizingConstant + 1/(2 * variance) * t(c(V)) %*% 
        Phi %*% solve(variance * GammaCheck) %*% t(Phi) %*% c(V)

    return(marginalLikeihood)
}

# Bayes factor
logBayesRatio = computeMarginalLikelihoodFixedLowercaseSigma(V, X, Gamma, variance) - 
    computeMarginalLikelihoodFixedLowercaseSigma(V1, X1, Gamma, variance) - 
    computeMarginalLikelihoodFixedLowercaseSigma(V2, X2, Gamma, variance)
logBayesRatio

##      [,1]
## [1,]   48

exp(logBayesRatio)

##           [,1]
## [1,] 7.008e+20

Bayes factor with fixed \( \Sigma \)

Marginal likelihood

With fixed/known velocity noise, equation from E. Fox, PhD thesis 2009, page 253 (F.10):

\[ p(V|\Sigma) = \frac{|K|^{d/2}}{|2\pi\Sigma|^{N/2}|S_{XX}|^{d/2}} \exp \left( \frac{1}{2}\operatorname{Trace}(\Sigma^{-1} VX^t S_{XX}^{-1} XV^t) \right) \] with \[ S_{XX} = XX^t + K \]

Hyperparameters

Sigma = variance * diag(1, dimension, dimension)
K = variance * B

Ratio of marginal likelihoods

computeMarginalLikelihoodFixedUppercaseSigma <- function(V, X, K, Sigma) {
    d = dim(V)[1]
    N = dim(V)[2]
    X[1:d, ] = t(scale(t(X[1:d, ]), center = TRUE, scale = FALSE))

    Sxx = X %*% t(X) + K
    normalizingConstant = d/2 * log(det(K)) - N/2 * log(det(2 * pi * Sigma)) - 
        d/2 * log(det(Sxx))
    marginalLikeihood = normalizingConstant + 1/2 * sum(diag(solve(Sigma) %*% 
        V %*% t(X) %*% solve(Sxx) %*% X %*% t(V)))

    return(marginalLikeihood)
}

# Bayes factor
logBayesRatio = computeMarginalLikelihoodFixedUppercaseSigma(V, X, K, Sigma) - 
    computeMarginalLikelihoodFixedUppercaseSigma(V1, X1, K, Sigma) - computeMarginalLikelihoodFixedUppercaseSigma(V2, 
    X2, K, Sigma)
logBayesRatio

## [1] 48

exp(logBayesRatio)

## [1] 7.008e+20

Bayes factor with random \( \Sigma \)

Hyperparameters

n0 = 4
S0 = diag(1, dimension, dimension)
S0 = variance * S0

Marginal likelihood

Equation from Ghosh et al., NIPS 2012:

\[ p(V|X,K,n_0,S_0) = \frac{ |K|^{d/2} |S_0|^{n_0/2} \Gamma_3 \left( \frac{N+n_0}{2} \right) }{ \pi^{dN/2} |S_{XX}|^{d/2} |S_0 + S_{V|X}|^{(N+n_0)/2} \Gamma_3 \left( \frac{n_0}{2} \right) } \]

Ratio of marginal likelihoods

computeMarginalLikelihoodRandomSigma <- function(V, X, K, n0, S0) {
    d = dim(V)[1]
    N = dim(V)[2]

    X[1:d, ] = t(scale(t(X[1:d, ]), center = TRUE, scale = FALSE))

    Sxx = X %*% t(X) + K
    Svx = V %*% t(V) - V %*% t(X) %*% solve(Sxx) %*% X %*% t(V)
    marginalLikeihood = 0.5 * d * log(det(K)) + 0.5 * n0 * log(det(S0)) + lgamma2(0.5 * 
        N + 0.5 * n0) - 0.5 * d * N * log(pi) - 0.5 * d * log(det(Sxx)) - (0.5 * 
        N + 0.5 * n0) * log(det(S0 + Svx)) - lgamma2(0.5 * n0)

    return(marginalLikeihood)
}

# Bayes factor
logBayesRatio = computeMarginalLikelihoodRandomSigma(V, X, K, n0, S0) - computeMarginalLikelihoodRandomSigma(V1, 
    X1, K, n0, S0) - computeMarginalLikelihoodRandomSigma(V2, X2, K, n0, S0)
logBayesRatio

## [1] 126.2

exp(logBayesRatio)

## [1] 6.581e+54

Second example: Two rotations

In this exmaple we simulate a case where joining the partitions has a lower probabilty, thus the Bayes factor is below 1.

# Two translation matrices
T1 = diag(dimension + 1)
T1[1, 3] = -3
T1[2, 3] = 0

T2 = diag(dimension + 1)
T2[1, 3] = 3
T2[2, 3] = 0

# Two rotation matrices
R1 = diag(dimension + 1)
angle1 = pi/10
R1[1, 1] = cos(angle1)
R1[1, 2] = -sin(angle1)
R1[2, 1] = sin(angle1)
R1[2, 2] = cos(angle1)

R2 = solve(R1)

# Composition of transformations
A1 = T1 %*% R1 %*% solve(T1)
A2 = T2 %*% R2 %*% solve(T2)

# Two new velocity fields
V1 = logm(A1)[1:2, ] %*% X1
V2 = logm(A2)[1:2, ] %*% X2
V = cbind(V1, V2)

# Visualize velocity fields and compute Bayes factors
bayesFactors = computeBayesFactors(V, V1, V2, X, X1, X2, Gamma, variance, K, 
    Sigma, n0, S0)


bayesFactors

## bfFixedLowercaseSigma      bfUppercaseSigma         bfRandomSigma 
##                     0                     0                     0

Fifth example: Adding i.i.d. normal noise

# Load library
library(MASS, quietly = TRUE)

# define hyperparameter
variance = 0.1
B = diag(c(100, 100, 1))
Gamma = B %x% diag(1, dimension)

Sigma = variance * diag(1, dimension, dimension)
K = variance * B

n0 = 4
S0 = diag(1, dimension, dimension)
S0 = variance * S0

# i.i.d. normal noise velocity field
noise = mvrnorm(dimension, rep(0, dim(V)[2]), sqrt(variance) * diag(1, dim(V)[2]))
plot.new()
createEmptyGrid(size)
visualizeVelField(noise, X, color = "black")

One rotation

# Show noise free field for comparison
V = logm(R)[1:2, ] %*% X
plot.new()
createEmptyGrid(size)
visualizeVelField(V, X, color = "black")


# Add noise
V = V + noise
V1 = V[, 1:61]
V2 = V[, 62:121]

# Visualize velocity fields and compute Bayes factors
bayesFactors = computeBayesFactors(V, V1, V2, X, X1, X2, Gamma, variance, K, 
    Sigma, n0, S0)
